From e3abc7593fb08584b9d0c96050ddf07f056f3fb6 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: reap-loop <reap-loop@localhost>
Date: Sun, 12 Jul 2026 02:00:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] cuda: fix 0036 cross-layer epoch bump defeated by 0034
 (0036a)

0034 stamps cache->slots[slot].valid = 0 as the FIRST statement of
cuda_stream_expert_cache_load_slot (defense-in-depth so a torn buffer
can never be observed as a valid hit). 0036 later added, lower in the
same function, a cross-layer victim epoch bump:

    cuda_stream_expert_cache_slot &entry = cache->slots[slot];
    if (cuda_inplace_resident_enabled()) {
        if (entry.valid && entry.layer != layer)   // entry.valid == 0
            cuda_inplace_epoch_bump(entry.layer);  // NEVER fires
        cuda_inplace_epoch_bump(layer);
        ...
    }

Because 0034 already zeroed entry.valid at the top, the guard
entry.valid is ALWAYS 0 by the time 0036 reads it, so the cross-layer
bump NEVER fires. Under the livemask dynamic admit/evict regime a
cross-layer eviction of an unpinned resident then goes undetected: the
other layer keeps a stale in-place slot map pointing at the repurposed
slot, and its decode GEMM reads the WRONG expert's weights -- silent,
non-bit-exact, counted as 0 misses.

Fix: capture the slot's (valid, layer) identity at function entry,
BEFORE 0034 zeroes valid, and base the cross-layer bump on the captured
values. entry.layer is not touched by 0034 so it still held the old
layer, but entry.valid did not; capturing both keeps the test
self-consistent and robust to any future reordering.

No env var, no success/failure-path change. When DS4_CUDA_INPLACE_RESIDENT
is unset the two captured locals are dead loads the optimizer drops and
the epoch-bump block is never entered, so the default engine stays
byte-identical to post-0036.

Follow-on to 0036 (applies after it); pairs with 0034.
---
 ds4_cuda.cu | 18 ++++++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 16 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/ds4_cuda.cu b/ds4_cuda.cu
index ca98236..5f59831 100644
--- a/ds4_cuda.cu
+++ b/ds4_cuda.cu
@@ -4493,6 +4493,16 @@ static int cuda_stream_expert_cache_load_slot(
         uint64_t down_expert_bytes,
         int defer_upload_sync,
         int prompt_like_batch) {
+    /* 0036a epoch-fix: capture this slot's PRE-repurpose (valid,layer)
+     * identity BEFORE 0034's `cache->slots[slot].valid = 0` stamp (just
+     * below) zeroes it.  0036's cross-layer epoch bump further down must
+     * test the identity the slot had on entry: reading entry.valid AFTER 0034
+     * always sees 0, so the bump for a genuine cross-layer eviction would never
+     * fire and that other layer's stale in-place slot map would keep pointing
+     * at this repurposed slot -- its decode GEMM would then read the WRONG
+     * expert's weights (silent, non-bit-exact, counted as 0 misses). */
+    const int      inplace_prev_valid = cache->slots[slot].valid;
+    const uint32_t inplace_prev_layer = cache->slots[slot].layer;
     /* 0034 stale-slot fix: stamp this slot invalid before the first buffer
      * write below.  If any of the copies that follow fail partway through,
      * the slot is left holding a torn buffer; clearing valid here (not just
@@ -4555,8 +4565,12 @@ static int cuda_stream_expert_cache_load_slot(
          * path for BOTH the evicted victim's layer and the admitted expert's
          * layer.  Bump both epochs so a stale fast-path reuse can never read a
          * repurposed slot. */
-        if (entry.valid && entry.layer != layer) {
-            cuda_inplace_epoch_bump(entry.layer);
+        if (inplace_prev_valid && inplace_prev_layer != layer) {
+            /* 0036a: test the PRE-0034 identity captured at function entry, not
+             * entry.valid -- 0034 zeroed it at the top, so the original test
+             * never fired for a real cross-layer eviction and left that other
+             * layer's stale in-place binding live over a now-repurposed slot. */
+            cuda_inplace_epoch_bump(inplace_prev_layer);
         }
         cuda_inplace_epoch_bump(layer);
         /* 0036 cache-first: pin the admitted expert on first touch (sticky) so
